of Evil (by Timothy O'Connor, Department of Philosophy, Indiana University), treats both the internal and external challenge posed by evil to theistic belief.V. Soul and Immortality (by J. P. Moreland, Department of Philosophy, Biola University), explores the substantiality and immateriality of the soul and the implications for life after death of the body.VI. Christian Theology (by Michael Murray, Department of Philosophy, Franklin and Marshall College), handles problems posed by the Trinity, incarnation, atonement, damnation and prayer.Presenting a sympathetic view of the topics it treats,Philosophy of Religion provides an ideal resource for studying the central questions raised by religious belief.Key FeaturesA combined anthology of readings and guide to the subjectFocuses on contemporary issues in the Philosophy of ReligionEmphasis placed on the Christian traditionHigh quality introductions to each section provide a survey of each topicCutting-edge readings chosen by specialistsProvides a sympathetic view of the topics it discusses  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aReligionxPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh1 aAlston, William P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChurchland, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, William Lane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Stephen T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDraper, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlint, Thomas P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFred